## 9. Improve mobile headings

Your mobile media rule changes the layout, but it does not reduce the 48px and 40px headings. Add:

```css
@media (max-width: 768px) {
    .page-header {
        height: 80px;
        padding: 16px 24px;
    }

    .content-container {
        display: flex;
        flex-direction: column;
        min-height: auto;
    }

    .left-content {
        order: 1;
        padding: 32px 24px;
    }

    .left-content h1 {
        font-size: 36px;
        line-height: 1.15;
    }

    .left-content h2 {
        margin-bottom: 28px;
        font-size: 30px;
    }

    .left-content > p {
        margin-bottom: 28px;
        font-size: 17px;
    }

    .right-illustration {
        order: 2;
        width: 100%;
        min-height: 360px;
        border-top-left-radius: 32px;
        border-top-right-radius: 32px;
    }

    .mascot {
        width: 360px;
        right: 50%;
        bottom: -90px;
        transform: translateX(50%) scaleX(-1);
    }
}
```

## Most important cleanup

Search the CSS file for each of these selectors and ensure there is only one active definition:

```css
.left-content
.left-content h1
.left-content h2
.left-content p
.sales-option
.confirm-btn
.btn-icon
```

Right now the browser is combining old and new declarations. That is why some parts match the design while others still use the previous sizing, weight, spacing, or colors.
